<HH> ============= Screen: Introduction ======================== </HH>

<IntakeGate ready="!@fba3_completion_checkbox.value">
<Markdown> </Markdown>
<Markdown id="fba3_introduction">
## Introduction

Two weeks have passed since your group helped Annie's roommate create an escape-focused behavior modification plan for Johnny's bedtime routine.

In this session, you will:

- Review **progress monitoring** data to evaluate how the intervention is going.
- Learn about **implementation fidelity** and why it matters.
- Identify areas where the plan was not followed correctly.
- Use AI to brainstorm **modifications** to improve adherence.
- Reflect on the overall experience.

Let's check in with Annie to see how things went.
</Markdown>
</IntakeGate>


<HH> ============= Screen: Progress graph + predict fidelity ===== </HH>

<IntakeGate id="fba3_predict_fidelity" ready="@fba3_interpretation_confidence.value">

  <!-- Front: see the data, predict what went wrong -->
  <Vertical>
    <Markdown>
## Progress Monitoring: Week 1–2

Annie's roommate tracked Johnny's bedtime over 5 babysitting sessions:
    </Markdown>
    <ObservablePlot id="fba3_week1_chart" title="Johnny's Bedtimes (Week 1–2)" format="js"><![CDATA[
const data = [
  { date: "9/5", bedtimeIndex: 0 },
  { date: "9/6", bedtimeIndex: 0 },
  { date: "9/7", bedtimeIndex: 1 },
  { date: "9/8", bedtimeIndex: 2 },
  { date: "9/9", bedtimeIndex: 2 }
];

function formatBedtimeLabel(index) {
  const labels = {
    "-0.25": "7:45 PM",
    0: "8:00 PM",
    1: "8:30 PM",
    2: "9:00 PM",
    "2.25": "9:15 PM"
  };
  return labels[index] ?? `${index}`;
}

return Plot.plot({
  width: 680,
  height: 300,
  marginLeft: 72,
  marginBottom: 48,
  marks: [
    Plot.lineY(data, {
      x: "date",
      y: "bedtimeIndex",
      stroke: "#111827",
      curve: "linear",
      strokeWidth: 3,
      clip: false
    }),
    Plot.dot(data, {
      x: "date",
      y: "bedtimeIndex",
      stroke: "#111827",
      fill: "#111827",
      r: 4,
      clip: false
    })
  ],
  x: {
    label: "Date",
    ticks: data.map((d) => d.date)
  },
  y: {
    label: "Bedtime",
    domain: [-0.25, 2.25],
    ticks: [0, 1, 2],
    tickFormat: formatBedtimeLabel
  }
});
]]></ObservablePlot>
    <Markdown>
The data shows that something isn't working. **Before reading the explanation, look at the graph and write what you think went wrong.** Consider: Is the plan itself flawed, or is something else going on?
    </Markdown>

    <TextArea id="fba3_week1_interpretation" rows="3"
      placeholder="Looking at the graph, I think the problem might be..." />

    <Markdown>Once you've written your interpretation, **select a confidence level below to see what actually happened.** (You won't be able to change your answer after selecting.)</Markdown>
    <ChoiceInput id="fba3_interpretation_confidence">
      <Key value="very">Very confident — I'm sure about this</Key>
      <Key value="somewhat">Somewhat confident — I think so but I'm not sure</Key>
      <Key value="guess">Just guessing</Key>
    </ChoiceInput>
  </Vertical>

  <!-- Back: show interpretation alongside the fidelity framework -->
  <Vertical>
    <Markdown>
## Your Interpretation

{{text2markdown(@fba3_week1_interpretation.value)}}

---

## What Actually Happened

- Johnny went to bed on time (8:00 PM) only on the first **2 out of 5** sessions
- Bedtimes got progressively later over the two weeks
- On one occasion, the roommate noted she didn't follow the plan exactly
- The escape behaviors seem to have gotten worse over time

The issue turns out to be **implementation fidelity** — how accurately and consistently the behavior plan was followed.

## Implementation Fidelity

Implementation fidelity refers to how accurately and consistently a behavior plan is implemented as it was designed. There are five key aspects:

1. **Adherence** — Are all steps of the plan followed as written?
2. **Dosage** — Is the plan used for the correct amount of time/frequency?
3. **Quality of Delivery** — Are the strategies implemented correctly and with the intended tone/approach (e.g., calm redirection vs. yelling)?
4. **Participant Responsiveness** — Is the child actually exposed to and engaged with the intervention?
5. **Program Differentiation** — Are other strategies (not part of the plan) avoided during implementation?
    </Markdown>
  </Vertical>

</IntakeGate>


